{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and harms of running tourism projects focused on wild primates?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across multiple sites, tourism projects for wild primates were associated with both benefits and harms. Benefits documented include increases in mountain gorilla numbers after touristic projects were initiated in Rwanda, Uganda and the Republic of Congo, alongside other interventions (1512); in Rwanda, immature mountain gorillas increased by 22% and snares declined by 30% after a tourism project began, alongside other interventions (1512); and black howler monkeys in Belize increased by 138% over 13 years following a tourism project, alongside other interventions (1512). Documented harms include decreases in Tana River red colobus and crested mangabeys in Kenya despite a tourism project, alongside other interventions (1512); increased stress in Tibetan macaques during an intensive tourism project with food provisioning and range restrictions, with infant mortality reaching 100% in some years (1512); and declines in population size and/or body size and group size for two lemur species in Madagascar after a tourism project, while one lemur species increased (1512). Related evidence on visitor health protocols shows mountain gorilla numbers increased by 168% over 41 years while sick/unwell researchers and visitors were excluded, alongside other interventions (1546), whereas a reintroduced orangutan population decreased by 33% over 33 years despite staff and volunteer medical checks, alongside other interventions (1546).",
  "action_ids": [
    "1512",
    "1546"
  ]
}

