{
  "query": "What are the comparative outcomes of different supplementary feeding strategies for primates?",
  "relevant_summary": "Time-limited supplementary feeding after release shows mixed outcomes: increases in a chimpanzee population after two months of post-release feeding in Tanzania [1528]; a decline in a golden lion tamarin population after one year despite supplementary feeding in Brazil [1528]; successful reunion of an abandoned infant muriqui with its group following supplementary feeding in Brazil [1528]; survival patterns ranging from only a minority of reintroduced primates surviving in studies from Brazil, Madagascar, and South Africa [1528], to a majority surviving at least 27 months for introduced chimpanzees in Guinea [1528], a majority of reintroduced primates surviving in Gabon, South Africa, and Vietnam [1528], and most lowland gorillas surviving for at least 9 months to 4 years in Gabon and the Republic of Congo [1528]. In contrast, providing supplementary food only during resource-scarce periods is associated with the majority of chimpanzees surviving at least five years in the Republic of Congo [1527], wild olive baboons surviving at least 17 years after drought-period feeding soon after translocation in Kenya [1527], and black-and-white ruffed lemurs maintaining diets similar to wild individuals under resource-scarce-period feeding in Madagascar [1527]. For providing nectar (including artificial nectar), no studies directly testing effects on primates were found [1331].",
